         "content_html" : "\n<p>Parmy Olson, in an opinion piece for Bloomberg:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>But this week marked a troubling difference. Facebookâ€™s\nannouncement that user numbers had dropped for the first time laid\nbare a long-neglected vulnerability: Digital advertising accounts\nfor 98% of Metaâ€™s revenue, and it also accounts for 81% of\nAlphabetâ€™s. Of the worldâ€™s five biggest tech companies, including\nAmazon Inc., Apple Inc. and Microsoft Corp., Facebook and Google\nare the least diversified.</p>\n\n<p>Though conventional wisdom says that conglomerates shouldnâ€™t put\nall their eggs in one basket, it is hard to knock a business model\nthat has been so successful. After all, people were calling Google\na one-trick pony back in the early 2000s because of its bet on\nads, and that bet has paid off handsomely two decades later.\nâ€œThrough most of the first decade the concept that Google would\nmake $10 billion was inconceivable to people inside the company,â€\nsays Sridhar Ramaswamy, who ran Googleâ€™s ad business for about\nfive years until he left in 2018.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Itâ€™s a little surprising to me that Googleâ€™s ad revenue is <em>down</em> to 81 percent of the companyâ€™s totalâ€‰â€”â€‰<a href=\"https://venturebeat.com/2012/01/29/google-advertising/\">10 years ago</a> it <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/oct/25/advertising-google-adwords\">was up around 97 percent</a>, like Facebookâ€™s today.</p>\n\n<p class=\"x-netnewswire-hide\" style=\"padding-top: 1.5em;\"><em>Link: <strong><a href=\"https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2022-02-03/facebook-and-google-s-ad-addiction-can-t-last-forever-thanks-to-tiktok-web3\">bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2022-02-03/facebook-andâ€¦</a></strong></em></p>\n"
