         "content_html" : "\n<p>Kevin T. Dugan, writing for New Yorkâ€™s Intelligencer:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>At times, an earnings report causes a stockâ€™s price to fall\nprecipitously only for it to moderate in the hour or so after,\nwhen the companyâ€™s executives calm down Wall Street by saying that\nall is not so bad. This time, it didnâ€™t work that way. In fact,\nFacebookâ€™s price continued to slide even lower. Zuckerberg, in his\ntrademark nasal drawl, seemed to acknowledge that the tide was\nturning against the business he has been running for 18 years as\nof this week. â€œThe balance of content that people see in feeds is\nshifted a little bit more towards stuff that isnâ€™t coming from\ntheir friends, which they may discuss with their friends, but itâ€™s\nkind of shifting towards more public content,â€ he said. The upshot\nhere is that the voyeuristic behaviors that made social media as\nwe know it so profitableâ€‰â€”â€‰what are my friends talking about? Who\ndid my high school ex marry?â€‰â€”â€‰were actually starting to fade.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Hereâ€™s a spitball theory: All social networks are fleeting. Theyâ€™re like hit TV showsâ€‰â€”â€‰they come and go. Facebook itself (i.e. the blue app) and Instagram arenâ€™t going to disappear, but their times as the new hotness are gone and will never return. (TikTok, which is currently the new hotness, will sooner or later suffer the same fate.)</p>\n\n<p class=\"x-netnewswire-hide\" style=\"padding-top: 1.5em;\"><em>Link: <strong><a href=\"https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2022/02/the-worst-day-of-mark-zuckerbergs-reign-at-facebook.html\">nymag.com/intelligencer/2022/02/the-worst-day-of-markâ€¦</a></strong></em></p>\n"
